From 0000000000000000000000000000000000000000 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Your Name <your.email@example.com>
Date: Mon, 02 Mar 2026 00:00:00 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] ANDROID: stop_machine: deadlock detection + full CPU dump +
 debugfs test hooks for migration thread stuck in multi_cpu_stop

Problem
-------
On Qualcomm platforms running Android16/GKI (Linux 6.12, Clang 19,
CONFIG_HZ=250, CONFIG_NO_HZ_IDLE=y), migration/N threads deadlock inside
multi_cpu_stop() when active_load_balance_cpu_stop() triggers a nested
stop_one_cpu_nowait() via:

  finish_task_switch()
    -> run_balance_callbacks()
      -> sched_balance_rq()  OR  balance_push()
        -> stop_one_cpu_nowait()    <-- re-entrancy while already inside
                                        stop_two_cpus / multi_cpu_stop

All online CPUs spin in rcu_momentary_eqs() waiting for the multi_stop_data
state machine to advance.  It never does.  The Qualcomm msm_watchdog fires a
bark ~10-11 s later; by then crash context (call stacks, stopper state, task
list) is partially lost.

"No of cores hotplugged: 0" in the crash log confirms the load-balancer
nested stop variant, NOT the hotplug variant.

This patch detects the deadlock after a configurable threshold (default 3 s),
emits a full per-CPU diagnostic dump, and calls panic() — capturing a clean
ramdump well before the Qualcomm watchdog fires.

==========================================================================
Fix 1: int cpu -> unsigned int cpu
==========================================================================
smp_processor_id() returns 'unsigned int'.  The original 'int cpu' is a
pre-existing type mismatch against cpumask_test_cpu(unsigned int, ...) and
per_cpu_ptr(..., unsigned int).  Clang 19 warns on every call site via
-Wsigned-unsigned-enum-conversion.  'err' retains int because msdata->fn()
can legitimately return negative error codes.

==========================================================================
Fix 2: Jiffies-based deadlock detection
==========================================================================
jiffies is updated by the timer tick interrupt — the same subsystem that
drives the Qualcomm msm_watchdog pet_timer kthread.

  - Pure memory read; zero hardware register overhead (unlike ktime_get()).
  - jiffies FREEZE when IRQs are disabled (DISABLE_IRQ / RUN states call
    local_irq_disable() + hard_irq_disable()).  time_after() stays false
    automatically — the timeout cannot fire during normal IRQ-off operation
    with no explicit state check needed.
  - CONFIG_NO_HZ_IDLE=y is safe: migration/N threads are SCHED_FIFO RT
    spinning in cpu_relax() and never call cpu_idle_loop(), so ticks fire
    at full HZ=250 rate during the PREPARE deadlock.
  - CONFIG_NO_HZ_FULL=n on this target — no concern.

Timeout values (CONFIG_HZ=250, from /proc/config.gz on target):
  STOPPER_TIMEOUT_JIFFIES (default) = 3 * 250 = 750 jiffies = 3000 ms
  Qualcomm bark_time                = ~9000-11000 ms = 2250-2750 jiffies
  Safety margin                     = ~6000 ms — panic always wins ramdump

==========================================================================
Diagnostics emitted before panic()
==========================================================================
  Sec 1: outer stopper fn + caller on detecting CPU (root cause)
  Sec 2: multi_stop_data state name, num_threads, thread_ack, inner fn
  Sec 3: cpu_online/active/dying masks
           (cpu_dying_mask==0 -> load-balancer variant; !=0 -> hotplug)
  Sec 4: per-CPU stopper state for ALL online CPUs (lockless snapshot)
  Sec 5: dump_stack() for the stuck migration/N thread
  Sec 6: trigger_all_cpu_backtrace() — IPI_CPU_BACKTRACE to all CPUs
  Sec 7: show_state() — SysRq-T equivalent

==========================================================================
Test infrastructure — CONFIG_DEBUG_FS only (zero overhead in production)
==========================================================================
  TEST 1  trigger_dump  (SAFE — no panic):
    echo 1 > /sys/kernel/debug/stop_machine/trigger_dump
    Exercises all 7 diagnostic sections with a synthetic multi_stop_data
    built on the stack.  Device stays up.  Verifies %pS, %*pbl, IPI
    delivery, show_state() output.

    NOTE: stopper_deadlock_dump() is NOT called directly here even though
    it is reachable (same TU; 'static' only limits external linkage).
    The reason is that stopper_deadlock_dump() ends with:
      pr_emerg("Calling panic()...")
    which would print a misleading banner in a safe no-panic test.
    The 7 sections are reproduced inline; only that final banner is omitted.

  TEST 2  simulate_panic  (WILL CRASH — ramdump device only):
    echo 1 > /sys/module/stop_machine/parameters/stopper_timeout_sec
    echo 1 > /sys/kernel/debug/stop_machine/simulate_panic
    Runs stop_machine() with a callback that busy-waits past the threshold.
    Exercises the REAL production path end-to-end:
      stopper_deadlock_dump() -> panic() -> ramdump captured.

  TEST 3  runtime timeout override:
    echo 1 > /sys/module/stop_machine/parameters/stopper_timeout_sec
    Reduces 3 s threshold to 1 s for faster stress-ng / hackbench loops.
    Boot cmdline: stopper_timeout_sec=1

==========================================================================
Android GKI compliance
==========================================================================
  - Single file: kernel/stop_machine.c only
  - No new exported symbols, no new Kconfig options
  - Clang 19 / LLD 19 compatible — no GCC-specific attributes
  - No dependency on CONFIG_SOFTLOCKUP_DETECTOR
  - trigger_all_cpu_backtrace(): <linux/nmi.h> — already in stop_machine.c
  - show_state(): <linux/sched/debug.h> — always present in GKI
  - jiffies / HZ / time_after(): unconditionally available
  - #ifdef CONFIG_DEBUG_FS guards all test code — zero overhead when =n
  - module_param() on built-in .c: valid — accessible via cmdline and
    /sys/module/stop_machine/parameters/ at runtime
  - IS_ERR_OR_NULL() covered by explicit #include <linux/err.h>

